---
import ContentPage from '../layouts/ContentPage.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config/site';
const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: `${SITE.url}/` },
  { name: 'Methodology', url: `${SITE.url}/methodology/` },
];
---
<ContentPage
  title="Methodology & Dosing Math"
  description="The exact formulas, constants, reference points, and sources behind every Pool Shock Calculator result."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <p>
    This page shows exactly how we calculate shock doses, so you can check our work.
    Every calculator on the site calls the same underlying engine described here.
  </p>

  <h2>The core relationship</h2>
  <p>
    Raising free chlorine (FC) by a given amount takes a predictable quantity of
    available chlorine per gallon. We calibrate to the widely published reference
    that raising FC by 1 ppm in 10,000 US gallons takes roughly 0.085 lb of pure
    available chlorine, then divide by the product’s available-chlorine percentage
    to get the actual product amount:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Raise needed (ppm)</strong> = target FC − current FC (never below 0)</li>
    <li><strong>Pure chlorine (lb)</strong> = 8.5&nbsp;×&nbsp;10⁻⁶ × raise × gallons</li>
    <li><strong>Granular product (lb)</strong> = pure chlorine ÷ available-chlorine fraction</li>
    <li><strong>Liquid product (fl oz)</strong> = 1.3375&nbsp;×&nbsp;10⁻⁴ × raise × gallons ÷ available-chlorine fraction</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Granular products are reported by weight (pounds, ounces, and approximate cups);
    liquids are reported by volume (fluid ounces and gallons), because that’s how you
    actually measure each one.
  </p>

  <h2>Reference points we calibrate against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Cal-hypo 68%: about 2 oz raises FC ~1 ppm in 10,000 gallons.</li>
    <li>Cal-hypo 73%: about 1 lb raises FC ~7.5 ppm in 10,000 gallons (the classic “1 lb per 10k” shock).</li>
    <li>Liquid chlorine 12.5%: about 10.7 fl oz raises FC ~1 ppm in 10,000 gallons.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Our automated test suite asserts these exact cases, so a change that broke them
    would fail before it ever reached the site.
  </p>

  <h2>Situation targets</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Situation</th><th>Target free chlorine</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Weekly maintenance</td><td>~10 ppm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Opening the pool</td><td>~15 ppm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>After heavy use / party</td><td>~15 ppm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cloudy water</td><td>~20 ppm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>After a storm</td><td>~20 ppm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Green / algae</td><td>~30 ppm</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Breakpoint chlorination</h2>
  <p>
    If you enter both free and total chlorine, we compute combined chlorine
    (total − free) and set a breakpoint target of 10× the combined chlorine — the
    level generally needed to destroy chloramines rather than add to them. The
    calculator uses whichever is higher: the breakpoint target or your situation’s
    target.
  </p>

  <h2>Volume estimation</h2>
  <p>
    When you don’t know your volume, we estimate it from dimensions: rectangles use
    length × width × average depth; round pools use π × radius² × depth; ovals use
    π × (length/2) × (width/2) × depth. Cubic feet convert to gallons at 7.48 gallons
    per cubic foot.
  </p>

  <h2>Assumptions and sources</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Results assume balanced water (pH 7.2–7.6) and reasonably accurate volume.</li>
    <li>High cyanuric acid reduces chlorine effectiveness and may require more than the calculated dose.</li>
    <li>Available-chlorine percentages come from manufacturer labels and safety data sheets.</li>
    <li>Free-chlorine targets follow public health guidance and certified pool operator breakpoint practice.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Data reviewed: <strong>{SITE.dataUpdated}</strong>. Maintained by {SITE.publisher}.</p>
</ContentPage>
